## Conclusion

The ASER 2016 survey for Gujarat Rural highlights significant progress in school infrastructure and access, yet challenges remain in learning outcomes. While enrollment rates are high and school facilities have improved, a substantial proportion of children in upper primary grades are not achieving grade-level reading and arithmetic skills. The disparity between government and private schools persists, with private school students generally performing better. The role of additional tuition classes is notable, with a significant percentage of children receiving paid support. Addressing the learning gaps, particularly in foundational literacy and numeracy, remains a critical priority for the education system in Gujarat.